results.name: Number of ordered factorizations of A025487(n) as A025487(j) * A025487(k).
comment: A025487(j) and A025487(k) need not be distinct.
Because multiplying two members of A025487 always produces a member of A025487, the value of this function for all nonmembers of A025487 is 0.
link: Amiram Eldar, Table of n, a(n) for n = 1..10000
example: 36 has three different ordered factorizations into two members of A025487 (36 = 1*36 = 6*6 = 36*1). Therefore, since 36 = A025487(11), a(11) = 3.
results.author: _Matthew Vandermast_, Nov 30 2010
